{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11697"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11697"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.26,0.06,0.08,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103191"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4312"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85628"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"390"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45075"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103191"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 34-year-old man presents with a two month history of a firm yet painless swelling in the left side of his neck (Image). He thinks it maybe getting slightly larger. He has no swellings anywhere else. Upon physical examination, the patient is not tender on palpitation and is firm in consistency. It is well defined and there are no associated swellings. The skin moves over the swelling. The mass did not rise upon tongue protrusion. The rest of the physical examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lipoma","Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Epidermoid cyst","Enlarged lymph node"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis swelling is situated in the left supraclavicular fossa. The thought that must come immediately to mind is whether this is a supraclavicular \u003Cstrong\u003Elymph node\u003C/strong\u003E. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroglossal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a midline structure, so that possible diagnosis can be excluded. \u003Cstrong\u003EBranchial cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are situated on the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, so this diagnosis does not fit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are within the skin and as in this case the skin moves over the swelling, this diagnosis is also excluded. A\u003Cstrong\u003E lipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a solitary painless, rubbery, smooth mass with a soft consistency that may be singular or multiple. They are non-tender on palpation and whilst they can be found anywhere on and in the body, they most typically occur on the trunk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this is an enlarged lymph node, the underlying pathology must be considered. Given the length of the history and absence of pain, this is unlikely to be an acute inflammatory problem. It could be a chronic infection such as tuberculosis, but given the absence of any other symptoms this is an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf most concern is whether this represents a malignant process. Such a malignant process could be primary disease (lymphoma) or metastatic. Further investigation (fine needle aspiration cytology) will be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is actually a case of metastatic lymph node disease from a papillary carcinoma of the thyroid. Papillary thyroid cancer is the most common type of thyroid cancer (\u0026gt;85%) with metastasis to the cervical lymph nodes occurring in up to 75% of cases. It is quite common for papillary thyroid cancer to spread into the lymph nodes of the neck before the cancer is discovered and diagnosed as it is a very slow growing cancer that usually presents asymptomatically.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A swelling in the supraclavicular fossa is most often an enlarged lymph node.","Papillary thyroid cancer is the most common type of thyroid cancer and often metastasizes to cervical lymph nodes."],"references":["Roland N, Bradley PJ. Neck swellings. BMJ. 2014 Jan 23;348:g1078. doi: 10.1136/bmj.g1078. PMID: 24458704. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24458704/","Schwetschenau E, Kelley DJ. The adult neck mass. Am Fam Physician. 2002 Sep 1;66(5):831-8. PMID: 12322776. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12322776/","Pynnonen MA, Gillespie MB, Roman B, Rosenfeld RM, Tunkel DE, Bontempo L, Brook I, Chick DA, Colandrea M, Finestone SA, Fowler JC, Griffith CC, Henson Z, Levine C, Mehta V, Salama A, Scharpf J, Shatzkes DR, Stern WB, Youngerman JS, Corrigan MD. Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation of the Neck Mass in Adults. Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2017 Sep;157(2_suppl):S1-S30. doi: 10.1177/0194599817722550. PMID: 28891406. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28891406/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85628"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11697"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17925"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com